    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-05-05T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-05-05T22:00:00-05:00" n="1"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/190: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary
                            of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-06T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 6, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 6—2:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>501. Following from American Consul General at Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“May 5, 1 p.m.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Heilungkiang troops, evidently acting in the interest of General
                                    <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_MC1">Ma Chan-shan</persName>,
                                are holding the Hu-Hai Railway from Hulan north and its rolling
                                stock to prevent advance along railway of Japanese troops some of
                                whom are entrenched near Sungpu and others located at points 2 and 5
                                miles north of Sungpu.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>Japanese troops have reached, by the steamers, Tungho on the
                                Sungari River, engaging small attacking forces in battle on the
                                way.</item>
                            <label>3.</label>
                            <item>Japanese troops have reached Mutan River just east of Hailin.
                                    <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WT1">Wang Te-lin</persName>’s
                                troops are holding railway line from river to Pogranichiiaya.</item>
                            <label>4.</label>
                            <item>Old Kirin troops have taken Pinghsien and are moving toward Harbin
                                and Maoershan. Bridges and track along the Eastern line of the
                                railway damaged in many places. Trains can only proceed as far as
                                Maoershan.”</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
